    "Note that for any z ∈ Ref, R(Q, z) ⊂ Q and moreover, if K is very large, then the measure of the set Q \\ z R(Q, z) is nearly the measure of Q.",
    "In the case d = 2, we have explicitly H 2 (Q \\ z R(Q, z)) = H 2 (Q)(1 -1 K) = r 2 -r 2 K.For each of the indicated rectangles on the picture, their natural partition into subcubes is also indicated, cf.",
    "For example, R = 7 i=1 Q(R, i), where each Q(R, i) is one of the very small squares inside the red rectangle R. If Q = Q z 1,...,z k i 0,...,i k, then each of the small squares is of the form Q z 1,...,z k+1 i 0,...,i k,i k+1 andR = R z 1,...,z k,( 2 M, 1 M) i 0,...,i k.Definition 5.11.",
    "Given integers K, M ≥ 2, the rectangle R 0 is called admissible of order 0 and each of the rectangles of the form R z 1,...,z k i 0,i 1,...,i k-1 is called admissible of order k. Each cube Q i is called admissible of order 0 and each cube of the form Q z 1,...,z k i 0,i 1,...,i k is called admissible of order k. If a cube or a rectangle is admissible of some order k, it is called admissible.",
    "We use the following notation (i) R k for admissible rectangles of order k, (ii) R ≤k for admissible rectangles of order at most k, (iii) Q k for admissible cubes of order k, (iv) Q ≤k for admissible cubes of order at most k.The set{p(R z 1,...,z k+1 i 0,...,i k): z k+1 ∈ Ref, i k ∈ {0,..., K -1}}is called the lattice of R z 1,...,z k i 0,i 1,...,i k-1."
